Batting stats charts¶

A short explanation of the meaning of each chart, in order. If not explicitly mentioned, the variables are normalized by the number of plate appearances:

  1. y-var: Base on Balls (i.e, walks), x-var: StrikeOuts - In theory, these variables should be negatively (i.e, inversely) correlated. Roughly speaking, aggressive batters which attack the ball thrown by the pitcher more often should walk fewer times because they are more likely to attack balls outside the strikezone, for which they would earn a walk.

  2. y-var: Normalized ops (i.e, walks), x-var: Difference between StrikeOuts and Base On Balls - In theory, these variables should be inversely correlated, because to obtain a large on base percentage (obp) (recall ops = opb + slugging), the batter must avoid getting striked out. This chart is particularly useful to determine the elite players - those with an ops above league average and a negative difference between StrikeOuts and Base On Balls - i.e, the top left corner of the chart).

  3. y-var: homeRuns, x-var: StrikeOuts - In theory, these variables should be positively correlated. Following 1., aggressive batters try to generate powerful contact with the ball more often. They will receive more homeRuns at the expense of more StrikeOuts. Elite players should be placed in the top half of the chart, towards the left.

  4. y-var: totalBases , x-var: hits, both as a league z-score - These variables are proportional - to score a single, double or triple, the batter must hit the ball. On average, the batter will receive one base per hit. This chart is relevant to determine outliers. That is, Aaron Judge is an absolute freak!
